          "body": "The chapter and the book end with three burials in the hill country of Ephraim: Joshua at Timnath-serah (vv. 29-30), Joseph's bones at Shechem in the field Jacob bought (v. 32), and Eleazar at Gibeah of Phinehas (v. 33). The closure is thick with meaning. Joseph's bones, carried from Egypt for over forty years (Exodus 13:19), are finally laid to rest *in the very plot Jacob purchased* (Genesis 33:19) — the promise of Genesis 50:25 is fulfilled in Joshua 24:32. The patriarchal narrative finds its long-promised burial. The king-figure (Joshua) and the priest (Eleazar) both die, signaling the end of the conquest era; the next book (Judges) will record Israel's collapse without them. But the chapter's final note (v. 31) is hope: *Israel served the LORD all the days of Joshua and all the days of the elders who outlived him* — memory of God's deeds sustains obedience exactly as long as the generation that knew them."
